What it means for you:

Key words:
• inequality

Don't forget:
Remember, ≤ means "less
than or equal to,"
> means "greater than or
equal to."
Borders of Regions
In Topic 4.5.1 you were dealing with regions defined by strict
inequalities - the ones involving a < or > sign. This Topic shows you
how to graph inequalities involving ≤ and ≥ signs too.
Regions Can Have Different Types of Borders
The region defined by a strict inequality doesn't include points on the
border line, and you draw the border line as a dashed line.
For example, the region defined by y> -x + 3 doesn't include any points
on the line y=−x + 3.
Regions defined by inequalities involving a ≤ or ≥ sign do include points
on the border line. In this case, you draw the border line as a solid line.
For example, the region defined by y ≥-x + 3 includes all the points on the
line y = -x + 3.
